title: Simulated Bivariate Ornstein–Uhlenbeck Model
Simulated Bivariate Ornstein–Uhlenbeck Model
text: Let measurement model intecept vector \(\boldsymbol{\nu}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\nu} = \left( \begin{array}{c}   0 \\   0 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let factor loadings matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Lambda} = \left( \begin{array}{cc}   1 & 0 \\   0 & 1 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let measurement error covariance matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Theta}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Theta} = \left( \begin{array}{cc}   0.5 & 0 \\   0 & 0.5 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let initial condition \(\boldsymbol{\eta}_{0}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\eta}_{0} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \boldsymbol{\mu}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0} \right) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\mu}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0} = \left( \begin{array}{c}   -3 \\   1.5 \\ \end{array} \right) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0} = \left( \begin{array}{cc}   1 & 0 \\   0 & 1 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let long-term mean vector \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\mu} = \left( \begin{array}{c}   5.76 \\   5.18 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let rate mean reversion matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Phi}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Phi} = \left( \begin{array}{cc}   0.1 & -0.05 \\   -0.05 & 0.1 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let dynamic process noise covariance matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \left( \begin{array}{cc}   2.79 & 0.06 \\   0.06 & 3.27 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\]

what: Using the simStateSpace::SimSSMVARFixed Function to Simulate Data
title: Simulated Bivariate Ornstein–Uhlenbeck Model
code: if (!require("remotes")) install.packages("remotes") remotes::install_github("ijapesigan/simStateSpace") library(simStateSpace) set.seed(42) data <- Sim2Matrix(   SimSSMOUFixed(     n = n,     mu0 = mu0,     sigma0_sqrt = chol(sigma0),     mu = mu,     phi = phi,     sigma_sqrt = chol(sigma),     nu = nu,     lambda = lambda,     theta_sqrt = chol(theta),     delta_t = delta_t,     time = time,     burn_in = 0   ) ) head(data) ##             y1       y2 time id ## [1,] -1.963528 2.532490  0.0  1 ## [2,] -2.551147 2.860833  0.1  1 ## [3,] -3.267033 2.904142  0.2  1 ## [4,] -4.042884 5.179311  0.3  1 ## [5,] -3.788725 3.874309  0.4  1 ## [6,] -3.209223 4.531096  0.5  1

text: transition matrix used examples taken Deboeck & Preacher (2015).

title: Trivariate Ornstein–Uhlenbeck Model
text: Let \(t = 500\) number time points \(n = 5\) number individuals. Let measurement model intecept vector \(\boldsymbol{\nu}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\nu} = \left( \begin{array}{c}   0 \\   0 \\   0 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let factor loadings matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Lambda} = \left( \begin{array}{ccc}   1 & 0 & 0 \\   0 & 1 & 0 \\   0 & 0 & 1 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let measurement error covariance matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Theta}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Theta} = \left( \begin{array}{ccc}   0.5 & 0 & 0 \\   0 & 0.5 & 0 \\   0 & 0 & 0.5 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let initial condition \(\boldsymbol{\eta}_{0}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\eta}_{0} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \boldsymbol{\mu}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0} \right) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\mu}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0} = \left( \begin{array}{c}   0 \\   0 \\   0 \\ \end{array} \right) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0} = \left( \begin{array}{ccc}   1 & 0 & 0 \\   0 & 1 & 0 \\   0 & 0 & 1 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let long-term mean vector \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\mu} = \left( \begin{array}{c}   0 \\   0 \\   0 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let rate mean reversion matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Phi}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Phi} = \left( \begin{array}{ccc}   0.357 & 0 & 0 \\   -0.771 & 0.511 & 0 \\   0.45 & -0.729 & 0.693 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let dynamic process noise covariance matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) given \[\begin{equation} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \left( \begin{array}{ccc}   1 & 0 & 0 \\   0 & 1 & 0 \\   0 & 0 & 1 \\ \end{array} \right) . \end{equation}\] Let \(\Delta_{t} = 0.1\).

text: data Data frame. data frame object data potentially multiple subjects contain column subject ID numbers (.e., ID variable), column indicating subject-specific measurement occasions (.e., TIME variable), least one column observed values. observed Character vector. vector character strings names observed variables data. id Character string. character string name ID variable data. time Character string. character string name TIME variable data. mu0 Numeric vector. Mean initial latent variable values (\(\boldsymbol{\mu}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0}\)). mu0 = NULL, vector zeros used. sigma0 Numeric matrix. Covariance matrix initial latent variable values (\(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\boldsymbol{\eta} \mid 0}\)). sigma0 = NULL, identity matrix used. mu_start Numeric vector. Starting values mu vector, , long-term mean equilibrium level. mu_start = NULL, vector means observed variables used. phi_start Numeric matrx. Starting values phi matrix, , rate mean reversion, determining quickly variable returns mean. phi_start = NULL, matrix zeros used. sigma_start Numeric matrx. Starting values sigma matrix, , matrix volatility randomness process. sigma_start = NULL, identity matrix used. theta_start Numeric matrx. Starting values theta matrix, , measurement error covariance matrix (\(\boldsymbol{\Theta}\)). theta_start = NULL, identity matrix used. sigma_diag Logical. sigma_diag = TRUE, estimate diagonals \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\). outfile character string name output C script model functions compiled parameter estimation.
